<article about="/us/blog/threat-insight/i-knew-you-were-trouble-ta456-targets-defense-contractor-alluring-social-media" class="node--type--blog-post node--view-mode--full node node-blog-full">
  



  <div class="breadcrumbs"><div class="nav-crumbs"><div class="breadcrumb__item"><a href="/us/blog" class="breadcrum__item-link">Blog</a></div><div class="breadcrumb__item"><a href="/us/blog/threat-insight" class="breadcrum__item-link">Threat Insight</a></div><div class="breadcrumb__item">
            I Knew You Were Trouble: TA456 Targets Defense Contractor with Alluring Social Media Persona          </div></div></div>

  <div class="blog-banner">
    <div class="blog-banner__image">      <picture>
                  <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1920_750/public/blog-banners/pfpt-mb-blog-banner-4.jpg.webp?itok=N1rpsea1 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1440px)" type="image/webp" width="1920" height="750"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1024_400/public/blog-banners/pfpt-mb-blog-banner-4.jpg.webp?itok=aljccDRM 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1024px)" type="image/webp" width="1024" height="400"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_768_375/public/blog-banners/pfpt-mb-blog-banner-4.jpg.webp?itok=q9Njtkoy 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 768px)" type="image/webp" width="768" height="375"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1920_750/public/blog-banners/pfpt-mb-blog-banner-4.jpg.webp?itok=N1rpsea1 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1440px)" type="image/webp" width="1920" height="750"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1024_400/public/blog-banners/pfpt-mb-blog-banner-4.jpg.webp?itok=aljccDRM 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1024px)" type="image/webp" width="1024" height="400"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_768_375/public/blog-banners/pfpt-mb-blog-banner-4.jpg.webp?itok=q9Njtkoy 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 768px)" type="image/webp" width="768" height="375"/>
                  <img loading="lazy" src="/sites/default/files/styles/image_768_300/public/blog-banners/pfpt-mb-blog-banner-4.jpg.webp?itok=pZA_wjma" width="768" height="300" alt="Mobile Devices" typeof="foaf:Image" />

  </picture>


</div>
    <div class="blog-banner__gradient-overlay"></div>
    <div class="blog-banner__heading-wrap">
      
      


<h1 class="blog-banner__heading">
      <span>I Knew You Were Trouble: TA456 Targets Defense Contractor with Alluring Social Media Persona</span>

  </h1>

    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="blog-content">
    <div class="blog-content__sharethis sharethis_toolbox sharethis_32x32_style">
      <div class="blog-content__sharethis_label sharethis__label">Share with your network!</div>
      <div class="blog-content__sharethis_buttons sharethis_buttons">
        <div class="sharethis-inline-share-buttons"></div>
        
<span class="addthis_button_subscribe at300b UNCONVERTED" title=Subscribe>
  <span class="at-icon-wrapper block-subscribe-button__trigger block-subscribe-button__addthis"></span>
</span>


      </div>
    </div>
        <div class="blog-content__metadata blog-content__metadata-author">
      <span class="blog-content__date">  <time datetime="2021-07-28T11:00:04Z">July 28, 2021</time>

</span>
        <span class="blog-content__author">
                JOSHUA MILLER, MICHAEL RAGGI, &amp; CRISTA GIERING
  
        </span>
    </div>
    <div class="node-full__body blog-content__body">  <h3 paraeid="{fd754fd8-5cb0-4ba3-ad17-a13cd83cc8a9}{16}" paraid="2056712258">Key Takeaways&nbsp;</h3>

<ul>
	<li paraeid="{fd754fd8-5cb0-4ba3-ad17-a13cd83cc8a9}{22}" paraid="1277763684">TA456, an&nbsp;Iranian-state&nbsp;aligned actor, spent&nbsp;years&nbsp;masquerading as the persona “Marcella Flores” in an attempt to infect the machine of an employee of an aerospace defense contractor with malware.&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{fd754fd8-5cb0-4ba3-ad17-a13cd83cc8a9}{37}" paraid="632561768">The malware, dubbed&nbsp;by Proofpoint as&nbsp;LEMPO, was designed to establish persistence,&nbsp;perform reconnaissance, and exfiltrate sensitive information.&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{fd754fd8-5cb0-4ba3-ad17-a13cd83cc8a9}{52}" paraid="811674645">TA456 actively targets smaller subsidiaries and contractors in support of efforts to&nbsp;compromise larger&nbsp;defense contractors using a supply chain&nbsp;compromise.&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{fd754fd8-5cb0-4ba3-ad17-a13cd83cc8a9}{65}" paraid="1231238603">While targeting defense contractors is not new for TA456, this campaign uniquely establishes the group&nbsp;as one of the most&nbsp;determined&nbsp;Iranian-aligned threat actors tracked by Proofpoint because of its significant use of social engineering, cross platform communication, and general persistence.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>

<h3 paraeid="{fd754fd8-5cb0-4ba3-ad17-a13cd83cc8a9}{84}" paraid="1624011908">Overview&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{fd754fd8-5cb0-4ba3-ad17-a13cd83cc8a9}{94}" paraid="338160000">Proofpoint researchers have identified a years-long social engineering and targeted malware campaign by the Iranian-state aligned threat actor TA456. Using the social media persona “Marcella Flores,” TA456 built&nbsp;a relationship across corporate and personal communication platforms&nbsp;with&nbsp;an employee of a&nbsp;small subsidiary of an&nbsp;aerospace defense contractor. In early June 2021, the threat actor attempted to capitalize on this relationship by sending the target malware via&nbsp;an ongoing email communication chain.&nbsp;Designed to conduct reconnaissance on the target’s machine, the macro-laden&nbsp;document&nbsp;contained personalized content and demonstrated&nbsp;the importance TA456 placed on the target. Once the malware,&nbsp;which is&nbsp;an updated version of&nbsp;<a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/2019/09/tortoiseshell-fake-veterans.html" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">Liderc</a>&nbsp;that Proofpoint has dubbed LEMPO,&nbsp;establishes&nbsp;persistence, it&nbsp;can&nbsp;perform reconnaissance on&nbsp;the&nbsp;infected&nbsp;machine,&nbsp;save the reconnaissance details to the host,&nbsp;exfiltrate&nbsp;sensitive&nbsp;information to an actor-controlled email account&nbsp;via&nbsp;SMTPS, and then cover&nbsp;its&nbsp;tracks by deleting that day’s&nbsp;host&nbsp;artifacts.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{fd754fd8-5cb0-4ba3-ad17-a13cd83cc8a9}{189}" paraid="1659934344">This campaign exemplifies the persistent nature of certain state aligned threats and the&nbsp;human engagement&nbsp;they are&nbsp;willing to&nbsp;conduct in&nbsp;support&nbsp;of&nbsp;espionage operations.&nbsp;In mid-July, Facebook disrupted&nbsp;a&nbsp;network of&nbsp;similar&nbsp;personas they attributed to Tortoiseshell.&nbsp;LEMPO, the malware,&nbsp;whose&nbsp;delivery&nbsp;Proofpoint&nbsp;disrupted, along with the network&nbsp;of personas,&nbsp;are&nbsp;attributed to TA456. This&nbsp;actor&nbsp;is believed to be&nbsp;loosely aligned&nbsp;with the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC)&nbsp;via association with&nbsp;the&nbsp;Iranian company&nbsp;Mahak&nbsp;Rayan&nbsp;Afraz&nbsp;(MRA), according to&nbsp;Facebook’s analysis.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{1c33a2fc-22d9-41eb-bde3-93bc9bdfcca2}{36}" paraid="296035502"><img alt="TA456" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="b80cd56e-c124-416b-8a84-414d5bdd9cd9" src="/sites/default/files/inline-images/TA456.png" width="2099" height="476" loading="lazy"></p>

<h3 paraeid="{1c33a2fc-22d9-41eb-bde3-93bc9bdfcca2}{32}" paraid="1680921839">Campaign Breakdown&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{1c33a2fc-22d9-41eb-bde3-93bc9bdfcca2}{51}" paraid="6904586">Proofpoint data shows that over at least eight months, “Marcella&nbsp;(Marcy)&nbsp;Flores” sent TA456’s target benign&nbsp;email&nbsp;messages, photographs, and a video to establish her veracity and build rapport with&nbsp;the intended victim.&nbsp;At one time, TA456 attempted to send a benign, but&nbsp;flirtatious&nbsp;video via a OneDrive&nbsp;URL.&nbsp;In early June,&nbsp;a TA456&nbsp;actor&nbsp;self-identified as&nbsp;“Marcy”&nbsp;sent another OneDrive link, this time masquerading as a diet survey&nbsp;(Figure 1).&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{1c33a2fc-22d9-41eb-bde3-93bc9bdfcca2}{51}" paraid="6904586"><img alt="Survey" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="b7b2bf0f-0a2a-487b-9697-c14411857ef6" height="668" src="/sites/default/files/inline-images/DIET%20SURVEY.png" width="1067" loading="lazy"></p>

<p paraeid="{1c33a2fc-22d9-41eb-bde3-93bc9bdfcca2}{51}" paraid="6904586"><em>Figure 1. The diet survey email sent to the target.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{1c33a2fc-22d9-41eb-bde3-93bc9bdfcca2}{130}" paraid="64383278">The OneDrive&nbsp;URL&nbsp;delivered a .rar&nbsp;file&nbsp;(dfddbd09ccea598c4841f1abbc927f1c661d85d4bd9bcb081f7c811212d8a64a)&nbsp;containing a .xlsm&nbsp;(Figure 2)&nbsp;(612bdfb4f6eaf920a7a41fa06de8d99f6ecf6ad147374efa6eb1d5aff91df558). Using previous conversation topics with the target, the .xlsm&nbsp;purported&nbsp;to be pandemic diet assistance and requested&nbsp;that the user enable&nbsp;content to access the privacy protected portions of the file.&nbsp;If&nbsp;the content is enabled,&nbsp;the&nbsp;macro&nbsp;will&nbsp;create and hide the directory \Appdata\Perflog&nbsp;and&nbsp;then write LEMPO, a very simple but ingenious plaintext stealer comprised of Visual Basic Script (VBS), to that directory (Schedule.vbs 1534f95f49ddf2ada38561705f901e5938470c1678d6a81f0f4177ba7412ef5b).&nbsp;After authoring the&nbsp;VBS, the&nbsp;Excel macro&nbsp;will&nbsp;add a registry key&nbsp;(HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run /v Schedule /t REG_SZ /d C:\Users\[redacted_username]\AppData\Perflog\Schedule.vbs /f)&nbsp;to ensure LEMPO is run&nbsp;upon&nbsp;user login.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{1c33a2fc-22d9-41eb-bde3-93bc9bdfcca2}{234}" paraid="386296783">&nbsp;<img alt="diet survey" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="dae7b710-2610-4509-aa65-4f3ac2c8f4dc" src="/sites/default/files/inline-images/MicrosoftTeams-image%20%288%29.png" width="1280" height="800" loading="lazy"></p>

<p paraeid="{1c33a2fc-22d9-41eb-bde3-93bc9bdfcca2}{234}" paraid="386296783"><em>Figure&nbsp;2.&nbsp;The diet&nbsp;survey&nbsp;.xlsm&nbsp;file.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{baa673e8-7747-45c5-b76e-f186101e4b3c}{56}" paraid="120249127">The macro in the&nbsp;Excel document&nbsp;also contains code to connect via HTTP POST to&nbsp;showip[.]net. The response, along with the results of "net use" and "netstat -nao" are stored in a hidden sheet within the .xlsm, reminiscent of the technique described in Facebook's July 15th announcement. Proofpoint analysts assess this may indicate code partially remaining from an earlier iteration of the tool that came before LEMPO or a desire for redundancy in TA456's reconnaissance tooling.&nbsp;</p>

<h3 paraeid="{954ede7d-7c80-4af7-a5a5-8bf905c82774}{38}" paraid="1608451494">LEMPO&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{954ede7d-7c80-4af7-a5a5-8bf905c82774}{38}" paraid="1608451494">The&nbsp;LEMPO reconnaissance&nbsp;tool is&nbsp;a&nbsp;Visual Basic&nbsp;Script&nbsp;dropped by&nbsp;an&nbsp;Excel&nbsp;macro.&nbsp;Leveraging built-in Windows commands&nbsp;it&nbsp;enumerates the host in a variety of ways, records the collected data and then exfiltrates the intelligence to an actor-controlled email&nbsp;account&nbsp;using&nbsp;Microsoft’s&nbsp;Collaboration Data Objects (CDO). CDO,&nbsp;previously known as OLE Messaging or Active Messaging, is an application programming interface included with Microsoft Windows and Microsoft Exchange Server products.&nbsp;While&nbsp;most of&nbsp;this analysis is based off&nbsp;the sample blocked by Proofpoint (1534f95f49ddf2ada38561705f901e5938470c1678d6a81f0f4177ba7412ef5b)&nbsp;in&nbsp;June 2021, we also identified&nbsp;&nbsp;a similar&nbsp;sample (da65aa439e90d21b2cf53afef6491e7dcdca19dd1bbec50329d53f3d977ee089)&nbsp;uploaded to&nbsp;a public malware repository with an upload date of June 2020.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<h3 paraeid="{954ede7d-7c80-4af7-a5a5-8bf905c82774}{194}" paraid="1286489612">Reconnaissance&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{954ede7d-7c80-4af7-a5a5-8bf905c82774}{200}" paraid="767382539">LEMPO collects&nbsp;the following information and records&nbsp;it to %temp%\Logs.txt&nbsp;</p>

<ul>
	<li paraeid="{954ede7d-7c80-4af7-a5a5-8bf905c82774}{214}" paraid="1397618629">Date&nbsp;and&nbsp;time&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{954ede7d-7c80-4af7-a5a5-8bf905c82774}{229}" paraid="1898393404">Computer&nbsp;and&nbsp;usernames&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{954ede7d-7c80-4af7-a5a5-8bf905c82774}{246}" paraid="1106796056">System information&nbsp;via WMIC&nbsp;os,&nbsp;sysaccount,&nbsp;&nbsp;environment,&nbsp;and&nbsp;computer&nbsp;system&nbsp;commands&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{20}" paraid="135663139">Antivirus products&nbsp;located in the “SecurityCenter2” path&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{29}" paraid="1361647616">Drives&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{36}" paraid="814388784">Tasklist&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{43}" paraid="1336962887">Software&nbsp;and&nbsp;version&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{54}" paraid="1051314007">Net&nbsp;users and&nbsp;user&nbsp;details&nbsp;</li>
</ul>

<p paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{77}" paraid="819909401">Following the connectivity check, detailed in the following section, LEMPO writes the following to&nbsp;%temp%\Logs.txt&nbsp;</p>

<ul>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{87}" paraid="1613787513">Firewall rules&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{94}" paraid="1157761721">List of running processes via&nbsp;Powershell&nbsp;Get-Process&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{105}" paraid="1658282760">IP config&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{112}" paraid="423114544">Domain hosts, users, computers, and local groups&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{119}" paraid="1922683701">Trusted domains&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{126}" paraid="1355033326">Network shares&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{133}" paraid="1167267855">Arp cache&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{140}" paraid="1928772120">Tracert&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{147}" paraid="1795304308">External IP (via showip.net)&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{154}" paraid="1900316967">Connections (netstat -nao)&nbsp;</li>
</ul>

<h3 paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{167}" paraid="1560031883">Connectivity&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{173}" paraid="271086559">Prior to the network focused reconnaissance, LEMPO checks&nbsp;connectivity by reaching out to Yandex, Google, Yahoo, Github, Mailchimp, Mega, Arxiv (an online&nbsp;academic&nbsp;repository specializing in electrical engineering and scientific research),&nbsp;and Twitter using ping and curl&nbsp;(Figure&nbsp;3).&nbsp;The June 2020 version of LEMPO includes&nbsp;only&nbsp;a connectivity check to ford[.]com.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{233}" paraid="740132908"><img alt="Text

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{238}" paraid="252995280"><em>Figure&nbsp;3.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{28cbd6df-d8ea-4c85-8f12-b09d634213c1}{252}" paraid="481884270">After finishing that additional recon, LEMPO moves Logs.txt from %temp% to \Perflog. LEMPO then checks to ensure the Registry Key previously mentioned has been added and then uses&nbsp;the&nbsp;findstr&nbsp;command&nbsp;to&nbsp;identify&nbsp;files&nbsp;containing “user,”&nbsp;“pass,”&nbsp;and “vpn.”&nbsp;The&nbsp;findstr&nbsp;command returns any matching lines&nbsp;which&nbsp;could&nbsp;collect usernames and passwords from the computer.&nbsp;Logs.txt is then compressed into Logs.zip&nbsp;</p>

<h3 paraeid="{51615c06-eb2e-4d28-bcf5-a1941076344d}{53}" paraid="1884023579">Exfiltration&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{51615c06-eb2e-4d28-bcf5-a1941076344d}{59}" paraid="1416610509">LEMPO&nbsp;uses&nbsp;hardcoded credentials with&nbsp;Microsoft’s&nbsp;CDO&nbsp;to exfiltrate the information over SMTPS&nbsp;on port 465. In the June 2021 version of LEMPO, TA456 uses the same&nbsp;Yahoo email address to send and receive the exfiltrated information. In the 2020 version of LEMPO, TA456 sent from a Yandex account to a&nbsp;Tutanota&nbsp;email account. Notably, the Yandex email within the 2020 version of the&nbsp;LEMPO&nbsp;implant masqueraded as&nbsp;large technology company focused on supporting the energy industry.&nbsp;After exfiltrating the information, LEMPO&nbsp;sleeps&nbsp;for 30&nbsp;seconds&nbsp;and then&nbsp;deletes&nbsp;both Logs.txt and Logs.zip.&nbsp;</p>

<h3 paraeid="{3dec2718-4acd-4a2f-9e93-0864a7be3e0a}{112}" paraid="1159397640">There’s Something About&nbsp;Marcy&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{51615c06-eb2e-4d28-bcf5-a1941076344d}{125}" paraid="8230036">“Marcella (Marcy) Flores”&nbsp;was&nbsp;conversing with the targeted aerospace employee since at least November 2020 and&nbsp;was&nbsp;friends with them on social media since at least 2019. Besides the Gmail account used for attempted malware delivery, Marcella maintained&nbsp;a&nbsp;now suspended&nbsp;<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/*/https:/www.facebook.com/marcella.flores.14019" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">Facebook profile</a>.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{51615c06-eb2e-4d28-bcf5-a1941076344d}{164}" paraid="1583111401"><img alt="Graphical user interface

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{51615c06-eb2e-4d28-bcf5-a1941076344d}{169}" paraid="2057248443"><em>Figure&nbsp;4.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{51615c06-eb2e-4d28-bcf5-a1941076344d}{183}" paraid="1707548149">Open-source&nbsp;research indicates&nbsp;“Marcella” interacted with TA456’s target on social media starting in late 2019.&nbsp;The earliest publicly available Facebook profile photo&nbsp;of “Marcella”&nbsp;was uploaded on May 30, 2018. Proofpoint’s analysis indicates the profile bears strong similarities to&nbsp;fictitious&nbsp;profiles previously used by Iranian APTs&nbsp;to socially engineer targets of intelligence value. The&nbsp;“Marcella”&nbsp;profile appeared&nbsp;to be friends with multiple individuals who publicly identify as defense contractor employees&nbsp;and&nbsp;who are&nbsp;geographically dispersed from&nbsp;“Marcella’s”&nbsp;alleged location in Liverpool, UK.&nbsp;On July 15,&nbsp;2021,&nbsp;<a href="https://about.fb.com/news/2021/07/taking-action-against-hackers-in-iran/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">Facebook announced</a>&nbsp;they had disrupted a network of Facebook and Instagram personas, including “Marcella’s,”&nbsp;they attributed to&nbsp;the&nbsp;Iranian-aligned actor.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<h3 paraeid="{ac87dca4-6227-4abb-bffe-137d517b58bf}{5}" paraid="1526788303">Targets&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{7fe6f068-782d-4cfb-8eb4-0b7a422ee134}{25}" paraid="1788049676">TA456 routinely conducts reconnaissance campaigns&nbsp;disguised as news related spam&nbsp;that target individuals employed by&nbsp;aerospace&nbsp;defense contractors. The targeting of&nbsp;U.S.&nbsp;defense contractors, particularly those supporting contracts in the Middle&nbsp;East,&nbsp;is consistent with historical Iranian&nbsp;cyber&nbsp;activity.&nbsp;Additionally,&nbsp;Proofpoint has observed&nbsp;TA456&nbsp;targeting&nbsp;individuals&nbsp;employed at&nbsp;multiple&nbsp;subcontractors&nbsp;and subsidiaries of larger defense companies. This is possibly&nbsp;an effort&nbsp;to target the&nbsp;primary&nbsp;contractor&nbsp;via less secure downstream component suppliers that share a network environment.&nbsp;Open-source&nbsp;research&nbsp;indicated&nbsp;the individual targeted&nbsp;by&nbsp;“Marcella”&nbsp;in&nbsp;this campaign&nbsp;works&nbsp;as a&nbsp;supply chain&nbsp;manager. This is consistent with TA456’s TTP of&nbsp;targeting business&nbsp;and&nbsp;information technology-related individuals&nbsp;within their target&nbsp;organization.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<h3 paraeid="{7fe6f068-782d-4cfb-8eb4-0b7a422ee134}{153}" paraid="915911354">Attribution&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{7fe6f068-782d-4cfb-8eb4-0b7a422ee134}{163}" paraid="856062807">Proofpoint attributes this campaign to TA456, an Iranian-aligned adversary focused on espionage efforts against&nbsp;defense&nbsp;industrial&nbsp;base employees and contractors, particularly those supporting efforts in the Middle East. TA456 overlaps with activity tracked as Tortoiseshell,&nbsp;and&nbsp;Imperial Kitten.&nbsp;On July 15, 2021, Facebook&nbsp;<a href="https://about.fb.com/news/2021/07/taking-action-against-hackers-in-iran/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">attributed</a>&nbsp;a portion of Tortoiseshell’s activity to&nbsp;Mahak&nbsp;Rayan&nbsp;Afraz&nbsp;(MRA), an Iranian IT company&nbsp;with ties to the IRGC.&nbsp;Based on previous&nbsp;malware analysis and&nbsp;historical&nbsp;open-source&nbsp;research, Proofpoint concurs with this attribution.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{7fe6f068-782d-4cfb-8eb4-0b7a422ee134}{228}" paraid="1762562491">Additionally,&nbsp;LEMPO&nbsp;shares multiple similarities with&nbsp;<a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/2019/09/tortoiseshell-fake-veterans.html" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">Tortoiseshell’s&nbsp;Liderc</a>, including extensive machine reconnaissance, exfiltration via email, hardcoded email addresses with similar formatting, and overall pattern of targeting companies and individuals aligned with the American defense industrial base.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<h3 paraeid="{7fe6f068-782d-4cfb-8eb4-0b7a422ee134}{245}" paraid="2040501967">Outlook&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{7fe6f068-782d-4cfb-8eb4-0b7a422ee134}{255}" paraid="844852123">TA456 demonstrated a significant operational investment by cultivating a relationship with a&nbsp;target’s&nbsp;employee over&nbsp;years&nbsp;in order to&nbsp;deploy LEMPO to conduct reconnaissance into a highly secured target&nbsp;environment within the defense industrial base.&nbsp;Facebook’s&nbsp;announcement&nbsp;demonstrated&nbsp;TA456 had established an extensive network of these personas&nbsp;dedicated&nbsp;to&nbsp;enabling cyberespionage operations.&nbsp;While Proofpoint did not observe&nbsp;the&nbsp;delivery&nbsp;of&nbsp;any remote access trojans or&nbsp;command and control&nbsp;channels&nbsp;like&nbsp;TA456’s&nbsp;<a href="https://symantec-enterprise-blogs.security.com/blogs/threat-intelligence/tortoiseshell-apt-supply-chain" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">Syskit</a>,&nbsp;the information potentially gathered by LEMPO&nbsp;could be operationalized in a variety of ways.&nbsp;These include&nbsp;the utilization of stolen VPN credentials, exploitation of vulnerabilities in the identified software, or the customization of&nbsp;more advanced&nbsp;malware delivered from&nbsp;“Marcella.”&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{a1be640b-591c-4695-ab2d-b25e4a763ebf}{87}" paraid="314539634">TA456’s&nbsp;dedication to significant&nbsp;social engineering&nbsp;engagement,&nbsp;benign&nbsp;reconnaissance of targets prior to deploying malware,&nbsp;and&nbsp;their cross platform kill chain&nbsp;establish&nbsp;TA456&nbsp;to be one of the most&nbsp;resourceful&nbsp;Iranian-aligned threats tracked by Proofpoint.&nbsp;The “Marcella Flores” persona is likely&nbsp;not the only&nbsp;one in use by TA456, making it important for&nbsp;those working within or tangentially to the defense industrial base&nbsp;to be vigilant&nbsp;when engaging with&nbsp;unknown&nbsp;individuals regardless of whether it is via work or personal accounts.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

</div>
  </div>
